There were many thousands of us young men who felt it was the right thing to do when we volunteered for duty in RSV in the middle sixties. I personally felt it was our responsibility to help another nation defend against the &quot;tyranny of bullies&quot;.  I have often what would have happend to the many &quot;Anne Franks&quot; of the world because &quot;good men&quot; stood by and did nothing.<br><br>
Are government was wrong in the way we conducted ourselves in the war with the McNamara and his &quot;Whiz Kids&quot; philosophy of &quot;no win&quot;.<br><br>
I really never hear anyone mention that perhaps as many as 2.5 million Asian peoples lost their live after we left.  The beautiful Mountain people of the Central Highland are no longer in their homeland.<br><br>
Just food for thought...Statistically, over 15 - 20 million people were killed in China through Mao's cultural revolution in the middle sixties.  Russia had killed around the same amount of their own people in the 40's &amp; 50's.<br><br>
A question to ponder...Who should stand up for the people who have no arms to defend themselves against the &quot;bullies&quot; of the world.  (ie.,Hitler, Stalin, Kru, etc.)  Situations in Bosnia, Rowanda(SP), numerous other places in the world where literally tens of millions of people have been murdered by the tyrany of the &quot;bullies&quot;.  <br><br>
Let me ask what is moral about doing nothing?  What is moral, ethical about not openly discussing the tens of millions who have been murdered just in the past 40 years.<br><br>
I hear people complain even today about Lt. Calley, (which they should), but I hear no condemnation from the same people about what happened to good people throughout the world when all these mass murderers were taking place. <br><br>
China still murders people for dissent.  The American soldier at least went to battle to defend everone's right to dissent.<br><br>
I ask again...which is moral...do nothing...or defend the defenseless.<br><br>
There is an old soldier's cry.  &quot;When banner's flaunt and buggles blow, I'm content to fill a soldier's grave for reasons I shall never know.&quot;<br><br>
Perhaps one of the reasons was to defend the defenseless aginst the tyranny of a few &quot;bullies&quot;.<br><br>
I would ask those who protested the war to think about not impugning the motives of those who served and died.  I honor their right to protest, but I would hope they would realize there are very mean, vicious, people in the world.  <br><br>
I once wrote a paper as if I was corresponding to Anne Frank, as if she were living in RSV, China, as if she were living during the time I was in the bush in RSV.  What would she have thought about the way we ignore so much evil in the world...while purporting to be good men.<br><br>
